<h2><a name="TOC-The-role-of-the:"></a>The role of the:</h2>
<h3><a name="TOC-PROJECT-BOARD"></a>PROJECT BOARD</h3>
<div>
<ul><li>Accountable to corporate/programme management for the success/failure of the project</li>
<li>Responsible for communication to external stakeholders</li>
<li>Project Assurance - sometimes delegated</li>
<li>Approval of Plans, Product Descriptions</li>
<li>Authorisation of commencements</li>
<li>Approve changes (unless a dedicated change authority in place)</li>
<li>Set tolerances for the six management aspects</li>
<li>Make decisions on escalated issues</li>
<li>Authorise project closure</li></ul><div>The Project Board comprises the Senior User(s), the Executive and the Senior Supplier(s) but it is not a democracy the ultimate decision is with the Executive.</div>
<div><span style="color:rgb(88,63,111);font-family:Palatino,Palatino Linotype,serif;font-size:1.5em;background-color:transparent;line-height:1.5"><br>
</span></div>
<div><span style="color:rgb(88,63,111);font-family:Palatino,Palatino Linotype,serif;font-size:1.5em;background-color:transparent;line-height:1.5">PROJECT MANAGER</span></div>
</div>
<div>
<ul><li><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">To run the project in a day-to-day basis and to ensure that the project produces the required products within the specified tolerances (the six management aspects) set by the Project Board.</span></li>
<li><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">To produce reports and plans</span></li>
<li><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">To manage information flows between the Directing and Delivering levels</span></li>
<li><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">Authorise Work Packages</span></li>
<li><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">Advise the Project Board of any deviances from the tolerances set forecast or actual</span></li>
<li><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">Implement and enforce the Configuration Management Strategy</span></li></ul>
<h3><a name="TOC-1"></a><br>
</h3>
<h3><a name="TOC-PROJECT-ASSURANCE"></a>PROJECT ASSURANCE</h3>
</div>
<div>
<ul><li>To monitor all aspects of the project independently of the Project Manager. This necessitates involvement with all processes.</li>
<li>To monitor the project with regard to primary interests Business, User and Supplier and to report to corresponding Project Board roles.</li>
<li>Monitoring involves checking the right people, methods, standards, procedures are being used for this project.</li>
<li><b>Business</b>: check the project remains desirable from a business perspective and provide guidance</li>
<li><b>User</b>: ensure that the project continues to meet User requirements and that procedures are in place to ensure it is</li>
<li><b>Supplier</b>: review the Product Descriptions and ensure quality procedures are adequate and enforced to produce the required products.</li></ul>
<div><br>
</div>
</div>
<h3><a name="TOC-CHANGE-AUTHORITY"></a>CHANGE AUTHORITY</h3>
<div>The Configuration Management Strategy must define levels of severity for requests for change (set by the Project Board). For some levels of severity a dedicated Change Authority may be specified to authorise the request for change. The role of the Change Authority is to assess and approve or reject the request or escalate if necessary.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<h3><a name="TOC-TEAM-MANAGER"></a>TEAM MANAGER</h3>
<div>
<ul><li>Team Manager(s) report to and take instruction from the Project Manager.</li>
<li>Plan, monitor and report on the team's work including any issues and deviations from tolerances.</li></ul>
<br>
</div>
<h3><a name="TOC-PROJECT-SUPPORT"></a>PROJECT SUPPORT</h3>
<div>
<ul><li>Set up project folders and general administration</li>
<li>Advise on tools</li>
<li>Distribute reports</li>
<li>Update logs etc</li>
<li>Whatever else needs doing to assist the PM</li></ul>
<h2><a name="TOC-The-difference-between-project-stakeholders-and-project-decision-makers"></a>The difference between project stakeholders and project decision makers</h2>
</div>
<div>Project stakeholders are organisations, groups or individuals with an interest in the outcome(s) of the project. They will be formally recognised in the Communication Management Strategy. Only some stakeholders will be decision makers notably Business, User and Supplier interests.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>All stakeholders have the potential to affect the success of a project &nbsp;(by delay etc).</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<h2><a name="TOC-The-purpose-of-the-Communication-Management-Strategy"></a>The purpose of the Communication Management Strategy</h2>
<div>The Communication Management Strategy contains a description of the <b>means</b> and <b>frequency</b> of communication to and from (bi-directional) parties both <b>internal</b> and <b>external</b> to the project.</div>
